remarks.format:
## Remarks

`SKFourByteTag` represents a four-byte (32-bit) tag used by OpenType fonts
and Skia APIs to identify tables, axes, and other named entities. Each byte
corresponds to one ASCII character, packed into a `uint` with the first
character in the most-significant byte.

For example, the weight axis tag `'wght'` is stored as
`(uint)('w' << 24 | 'g' << 16 | 'h' << 8 | 't')`.

The struct can be constructed from four individual characters, from a raw
`uint`, or by parsing a string with <xref:SkiaSharp.SKFourByteTag.Parse(System.String)>.
It converts implicitly to and from `uint`.

## Examples

```csharp
// Construct from characters.
var wght = new SKFourByteTag('w', 'g', 'h', 't');

// Parse from a string (pads with spaces if shorter than 4 chars).
var wdth = SKFourByteTag.Parse("wdth");

// Round-trip through uint.
uint raw = wght;
SKFourByteTag back = raw;

Console.WriteLine(wght.ToString()); // "wght"
```
